      <memberdef kind="function" id="radiation_8h_1acb8273fe5b2026c98166e10f887c5948" prot="public" static="no" const="no" explicit="no" inline="no" virt="non-virtual">
        <type>__device__ double</type>
        <definition>__device__ double GPU_alpha_inv_abs</definition>
        <argsstring>(const double nu, const double Thetae, const double Ne, const double B, double theta, cudaTextureObject_t besselTexObj)</argsstring>
        <name>GPU_alpha_inv_abs</name>
        <param>
          <type>const double</type>
          <declname>nu</declname>
        </param>
        <param>
          <type>const double</type>
          <declname>Thetae</declname>
        </param>
        <param>
          <type>const double</type>
          <declname>Ne</declname>
        </param>
        <param>
          <type>const double</type>
          <declname>B</declname>
        </param>
        <param>
          <type>double</type>
          <declname>theta</declname>
        </param>
        <param>
          <type>cudaTextureObject_t</type>
          <declname>besselTexObj</declname>
        </param>
        <briefdescription>
<para>Calculates the Lorentz invariant absorption coefficient via Kirchhoff&apos;s Law. </para>
        </briefdescription>
        <detaileddescription>
<para>This function determines the invariant absorption coefficient $\nu \alpha_{a}$ by relating the invariant emissivity to the invariant Planck function (source function).</para>
<para>Based on Kirchhoff&apos;s Law of Thermal Radiation, the absorption coefficient <formula id="207">$\alpha_\nu$</formula> is the ratio of emissivity to the Planck function: [ \alpha_\nu = \frac{j_\nu}{B_\nu} ] In terms of the invariant quantities provided by the internal helper functions: [ \nu \alpha_\nu = \frac{j_\nu / \nu^2}{B_\nu / \nu^3} ]</para>
<para><parameterlist kind="param"><parameteritem>
<parameternamelist>
<parametername>nu</parametername>
</parameternamelist>
<parameterdescription>
<para>Photon frequency in the fluid frame (Hz). </para>
</parameterdescription>
</parameteritem>
<parameteritem>
<parameternamelist>
<parametername>Thetae</parametername>
</parameternamelist>
<parameterdescription>
<para>Dimensionless electron temperature <formula id="203">$\Theta_\rm{e} $</formula>. </para>
</parameterdescription>
</parameteritem>
<parameteritem>
<parameternamelist>
<parametername>Ne</parametername>
</parameternamelist>
<parameterdescription>
<para>Electron number density <formula id="204">$N_e$</formula> (cm <formula id="205">$^{-3}$</formula>). </para>
</parameterdescription>
</parameteritem>
<parameteritem>
<parameternamelist>
<parametername>B</parametername>
</parameternamelist>
<parameterdescription>
<para>Magnetic field strength (Gauss). </para>
</parameterdescription>
</parameteritem>
<parameteritem>
<parameternamelist>
<parametername>theta</parametername>
</parameternamelist>
<parameterdescription>
<para>Pitch angle between photon and magnetic field. </para>
</parameterdescription>
</parameteritem>
<parameteritem>
<parameternamelist>
<parametername>besselTexObj</parametername>
</parameternamelist>
<parameterdescription>
<para>CUDA texture for Bessel function lookups. </para>
</parameterdescription>
</parameteritem>
</parameterlist>
<simplesect kind="return"><para>The invariant absorption coefficient <formula id="208">$\nu \alpha_{a}$</formula> [units: Hz <formula id="206">$ \rm{cm}^{-1} $</formula>].</para>
</simplesect>
<simplesect kind="note"><para>A small epsilon ( <formula id="209">$ 10^{-100} $</formula>) is added to the denominator to prevent division by zero. </para>
</simplesect>
</para>
        </detaileddescription>
        <inbodydescription>
